{"title_page": "Joan Tarika Lewis", "text_new": "'''Joan Tarika Lewis''' (a.k.a. '''Tarika Lewis''', '''Tarika Matilaba''') is a [[Visual arts|visual artist]], musician, author, and [[Activism|political activist]]. Lewis was born Joan Angela Lewis in [[Oakland]], [[California]], to [[John Henry Lewis]] and Florence (Reid) Lewis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Joan-Lewis/6000000040308369924|title=Joan Tarika Lewis|website=geni_family_tree|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nLewis grew up in Oakland, California during the 1950s and 1960s [[Civil rights movement|Civil Rights Movement]]. Oakland was a hub for civil unrest due to the high prevalence of police brutality, and the continued segregation of the city due to white flight out of the \u201cFlatlands\u201d and into the Foothills.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The revolution has come : Black power, gender, and the Black Panther Party in Oakland|last=1970-|first=Spencer, Robyn C.|isbn=978-0822362869|location=Durham|oclc=944380346|date=2016-12-02|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/revolutionhascom00spen}}</ref> Lewis studied at [[Oakland Technical High School|Oakland Tech]], following in the steps of other Black Panther Party leaders such as [[Bobby Hutton]] and [[Reggie Forte|Reginald Forte]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Before becoming involved in racial politics, her parents wanted her to pursue a Jazz career, as she was an accomplished violinist in high school.<ref name=\":1\" /> During high school she co-founded the Black Student Union and staged [[sit-in]]s to demand the implementation of a Black Studies course as well as black history club.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book|title=The Black Panther party (reconsidered)|last1=Jones|first1=ed. by Charles E.|date=1998|publisher=Black Classic Press|isbn=0933121962|location=Baltimore|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780933121966/page/307 307]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780933121966/page/307}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://oaklandtech.com/staff/centennial/2016/02/17/tarika-lewis-67/|title=Tarika Lewis '67|date=2016-02-17|work=Oakland Tech Centennial|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-US}}</ref> Lewis drew her inspiration for these demands from student activists at [[Merritt College]] who were also demanding black studies courses.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Up against the wall : violence in the making and unmaking of the Black Panther Party|last=1969-|first=Austin, Curtis J.|date=2006|publisher=University of Arkansas Press|isbn=1557288755|location=Fayetteville|oclc=649942374}}</ref> Lewis began visiting [[Merritt College]] with her cousins when she was 16 to attend forums on black history and culture.<ref name=\":0\" /> Here she came into contact with the founding members of the Black Panther Party, [[Bobby Seale]] and [[Huey P. Newton|Huey Newton]], and was inspired by their visions of black nationalism and radical cultural and community preservation.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Lewis also came to be interested in the black panther party because of their Community Survival Programs they set up in high schools and community centers around Oakland.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/contemporaryyout0000unse|title=Contemporary youth culture : an international encyclopedia|date=2006|publisher=Greenwood Press|others=Steinberg, Shirley R., 1952-, Parmar, Priya., Richard, Birgit.|isbn=9780313327162|location=Westport, Conn.|oclc=61463631}}</ref> The community survival projects included programs like Free Breakfast for Children, Free Food Program, and Child Development Center.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Black Panther Party ==\nIn the spring of 1967, Lewis became the first woman to join the [[Black Panther Party]], at the age of 16.<ref name=\":1\" /> She dropped out of high school and made the decision to put her jazz career on hold in order to help the movement.<ref name=\":0\" /> She quickly rose in the ranks of the party, completing political education classes mandated by the party, and training in weaponry. When male panthers questioned her abilities as a marksman because of her gender, Lewis challenged them to come to the range and see if they could match her straight shot.<ref name=\":0\" /> Lewis was later appointed as a local Lieutenant, and helped train new recruits and teach drill classes.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nLewis continued her involvement in the Black Panther Party as one of the party's first revolutionary graphic artists, through her drawings and other artwork in [[The Black Panther (newspaper)|''The Black Panther'' (newspaper]]).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Remaking Black power : how Black women transformed an era|last=D.|first=Farmer, Ashley|isbn=978-1469634371|location=Chapel Hill|oclc=975491060|year = 2017}}</ref> Lewis contributed over forty images to the newspaper between 1967 and 1969 under the pen name \"Matilaba\". Most of the artwork that came out of the newspaper and the party itself is attributed to Emory Douglas, yet Lewis' drawings were prominently featured alongside his. Lewis worked as his assistant during her time spent in the part. Her work was easily identified by its thin pen strokes, and the light shading that outlined her usually militant female caricatures. Lewis' art usually represented common themes of the newspaper, including demonizations of the police as \"pigs\", as well as depictions of armed panthers, which reinforced Black Americans struggles against police brutality.<ref name=\":3\" /> What made her art stand out was its depictions of armed black women panthers rather than black men, a shift from the very masculine representation of militant self-defense usually pictured in the newspaper. Through both her artwork, as well as her involvement in training camps and police patrols, Lewis created a space for black women to embody the image of radical defenders of the community and culture.<ref name=\":3\" /> Lewis left the Black Panther Party in January 1969.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Art career ==\nAfter leaving the party Lewis became a graphic artist and Jazz violinist, yet she continued to engage with issues of community development heralded by the Black panther Party. She toured internationally with saxophonist [[John Handy]] and went on to teach visual arts as well as Jazz to inner city youth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ousd.org/Page/7569|title=Performing Arts / Staff Bios|website=www.ousd.org|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> She also is the founder of the Oakland Black String Ensemble. When working with her visual art skills, Lewis acts as an Art Instructor/Counselor at the Healthy Babies Project, where she helps women use visual art to represent and understand trauma due to substance abuse.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nLewis is also the author of ''Panther: A Pictorial History of the Black Panthers and the Story Behind the Film'' and also worked on the 1995 ''[[Panther (film)|Panther]]'' movie with Mario Van Peebles. In the film she acted as a consultant, and even had a minor acting role.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2001 she was awarded the [[Congressional Award|Congressional Recognition Award]] for \"Performing Artist and Recognition of Community Work\".<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bayyoutharts.org/?page_id=73|title=Strings of Soul (Tarika Lewis) \u2013 Bay Area Youth Arts|website=www.bayyoutharts.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Black Panther Party}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewis, Joan Tarika}}\n[[Category:Members of the Black Panther Party]]\n[[Category:Jazz violinists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century violinists]]\n", "text_old": "'''Joan Tarika Lewis''' (a.k.a. '''Tarika Lewis''', '''Tarika Matilaba''') is a [[Visual arts|visual artist]], musician, author, and [[Activism|political activist]]. Lewis was born Joan Angela Lewis in [[Oakland]], [[California]], to [[John Henry Lewis]] and Florence (Reid) Lewis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Joan-Lewis/6000000040308369924|title=Joan Tarika Lewis|website=geni_family_tree|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nLewis grew up in Oakland, California during the 1950s and 1960s [[Civil rights movement|Civil Rights Movement]]. Oakland was a hub for civil unrest due to the high prevalence of police brutality, and the continued segregation of the city due to white flight out of the \u201cFlatlands\u201d and into the Foothills.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The revolution has come : Black power, gender, and the Black Panther Party in Oakland|last=1970-|first=Spencer, Robyn C.|isbn=978-0822362869|location=Durham|oclc=944380346|date=2016-12-02|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/revolutionhascom00spen}}</ref> Lewis studied at [[Oakland Technical High School|Oakland Tech]], following in the steps of other Black Panther Party leaders such as [[Bobby Hutton]] and [[Reggie Forte|Reginald Forte]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Before becoming involved in racial politics, her parents wanted her to pursue a Jazz career, as she was an accomplished violinist in high school.<ref name=\":1\" /> During high school she co-founded the Black Student Union and staged [[sit-in]]s to demand the implementation of a Black Studies course as well as black history club.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book|title=The Black Panther party (reconsidered)|last1=Jones|first1=ed. by Charles E.|date=1998|publisher=Black Classic Press|isbn=0933121962|location=Baltimore|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780933121966/page/307 307]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780933121966/page/307}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://oaklandtech.com/staff/centennial/2016/02/17/tarika-lewis-67/|title=Tarika Lewis '67|date=2016-02-17|work=Oakland Tech Centennial|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-US}}</ref> Lewis drew her inspiration for these demands from student activists at [[Merritt College]] who were also demanding black studies courses.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Up against the wall : violence in the making and unmaking of the Black Panther Party|last=1969-|first=Austin, Curtis J.|date=2006|publisher=University of Arkansas Press|isbn=1557288755|location=Fayetteville|oclc=649942374}}</ref> Lewis began visiting [[Merritt College]] with her cousins when she was 16 to attend forums on black history and culture.<ref name=\":0\" /> Here she came into contact with the founding members of the Black Panther Party, [[Bobby Seale]] and [[Huey P. Newton|Huey Newton]], and was inspired by their visions of black nationalism and radical cultural and community preservation.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Lewis also came to be interested in the black panther party because of their Community Survival Programs they set up in high schools and community centers around Oakland.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/contemporaryyout0000unse|title=Contemporary youth culture : an international encyclopedia|date=2006|publisher=Greenwood Press|others=Steinberg, Shirley R., 1952-, Parmar, Priya., Richard, Birgit.|isbn=9780313327162|location=Westport, Conn.|oclc=61463631}}</ref> The community survival projects included programs like Free Breakfast for Children, Free Food Program, and Child Development Center.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Black Panther Party ==\nIn the spring of 1967, Lewis became the first woman to join the [[Black Panther Party]], at the age of 16.<ref name=\":1\" /> She dropped out of high school and made the decision to put her jazz career on hold in order to help the movement.<ref name=\":0\" /> She quickly rose in the ranks of the party, completing political education classes mandated by the party, and training in weaponry. When male panthers questioned her abilities as a marksman because of her gender, Lewis challenged them to come to the range and see if they could match her straight shot.<ref name=\":0\" /> Lewis was later appointed as a local Lieutenant, and helped train new recruits and teach drill classes.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nLewis continued her involvement in the Black Panther Party as one of the party's first revolutionary graphic artists, through her drawings and other artwork in [[The Black Panther (newspaper)|''The Black Panther'' (newspaper]]).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Remaking Black power : how Black women transformed an era|last=D.|first=Farmer, Ashley|isbn=978-1469634371|location=Chapel Hill|oclc=975491060|year = 2017}}</ref> Lewis contributed over forty images to the newspaper between 1967 and 1969 under the pen name \"Matilaba\". Most of the artwork that came out of the newspaper and the party itself is attributed to Emory Douglas, yet Lewis' drawings were prominently featured alongside his. Lewis worked as his assistant during her time spent in the part. Her work was easily identified by its thin pen strokes, and the light shading that outlined her usually militant female caricatures. Lewis' art usually represented common themes of the newspaper, including demonizations of the police as \"pigs\", as well as depictions of armed panthers, which reinforced Black Americans struggles against police brutality.<ref name=\":3\" /> What made her art stand out was its depictions of armed black women panthers rather than black men, a shift from the very masculine representation of militant self-defense usually pictured in the newspaper. Through both her artwork, as well as her involvement in training camps and police patrols, Lewis created a space for black women to embody the image of radical defenders of the community and culture.<ref name=\":3\" /> Lewis left the Black Panther Party in January 1969.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Art career ==\nAfter leaving the party Lewis became a graphic artist and Jazz violinist, yet she continued to engage with issues of community development heralded by the Black panther Party. She toured internationally with saxophonist [[John Handy]] and went on to teach visual arts as well as Jazz to inner city youth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ousd.org/Page/7569|title=Performing Arts / Staff Bios|website=www.ousd.org|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> She also is the founder of the Oakland Black String Ensemble. When working with her visual art skills, Lewis acts as an Art Instructor/Counselor at the Healthy Babies Project, where she helps women use visual art to represent and understand trauma due to substance abuse.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nLewis is also the author of ''Panther: A Pictorial History of the Black Panthers and the Story Behind the Film'' and also worked on the 1995 ''[[Panther (film)|Panther]]'' movie with Mario Van Peebles. In the film she acted as a consultant, and even had a minor acting role.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2001 she was awarded the [[Congressional Award|Congressional Recognition Award]] for \"Performing Artist and Recognition of Community Work\".<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bayyoutharts.org/?page_id=73|title=Strings of Soul (Tarika Lewis) \u2013 Bay Area Youth Arts|website=www.bayyoutharts.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Black Panther Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewis, Joan Tarika}}\n[[Category:Members of the Black Panther Party]]\n[[Category:Jazz violinists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century violinists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joan_Tarika_Lewis"}
{"title_page": "Jo Jo Adams", "text_new": "'''Joel Adams''' (c.1918 &ndash; February 27, 1988),<ref name=\"bare\">{{cite book| first1= Bob| last1= Eagle| first2= Eric S.| last2= LeBlanc| year= 2013| title= Blues - A Regional Experience| publisher= Praeger Publishers| location= Santa Barbara| pages=534 | isbn= 978-0313344237}}</ref> sometimes credited as '''Doctor Jo-Jo Adams''', was an [[United States|American]] [[jump blues]] singer, comedian, dancer, and [[MC]], who recorded in the 1940s and 1950s.\n\nHe was born in a rural area of [[Alabama]], and sang with the Big Four Gospel Jubilee Singers before moving to [[Chicago]] in the early 1940s.  He then began performing in clubs on the [[South Side of Chicago]], adopting a style derivative of [[Cab Calloway]], wearing a [[tuxedo]] with extended [[Tailcoat|tails]] that would swing around while he danced.  He said: \"I introduced color to the stage. My tailor-made tails that were 55 inches long - when I spun around you could shoot dice on them!\"<ref name=penny>[http://www.rockabilly.nl/references/messages/jo_jo_adams.htm  Dave Penny, \"Jo Jo Adams\", ''Black Cat Rockabilly'']. Retrieved 2 April 2014</ref>\n\nIn 1946 he made his first recording, \"Jo Jo Blues\", with bandleader Freddie Williams for the Melody Lane [[record label]], soon to be renamed [[Hy-Tone]].  He also recorded for Hy-Tone with guitarist [[Floyd Smith (musician)|Floyd Smith]], including the [[marijuana]]-related song \"When I'm In My Tea\"; and recorded for the [[Aladdin Records|Aladdin]] label in [[Los Angeles]] with [[Maxwell Davis]]' band. After returning to Chicago, he recorded under [[Tom Archia]]'s supervision for the [[Aristocrat Records|Aristocrat]] label run by [[Leonard Chess]].<ref name=marion>[http://home.earthlink.net/~v1tiger/drjojo.html  J. C. Marion, \"Doctor Jo Jo Adams\", ''Jamm Upp'' #46, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303200105/http://home.earthlink.net/~v1tiger/drjojo.html |date=2016-03-03 }}. Retrieved 2 April 2014</ref>  His recordings there included \"Cabbage Head\", a version of the folk song \"Our Gudeman\", also known as \"[[Seven Drunken Nights]]\".<ref name=penny/>\n\nAdams appeared in the 1949 all-[[African American]] [[revue]] film ''[[Burlesque in Harlem]]'', performing a risqu\u00e9 version of \"[[The Hucklebuck]]\".  The following year, he began appearing regularly with [[Memphis Slim]] and [[Terry Timmons]] in clubs in Chicago, and at the end of the year performed at a New Year's Eve show with [[Lester Young]] and others.  He also performed in his own revue, the \"Jo Jo Show\", which at various times featured singers [[Joe Williams (jazz singer)|Joe Williams]], [[Willie Mabon]], Bill Pinkard, and the Melvin Moore Combo.<ref name=marion/> He made his last recordings in 1952 and 1953, for the [[Chance Records|Chance]] and [[Parrot Records (blues label)|Parrot]] labels; some of the latter recordings were arranged by [[Sun Ra]].<ref name=penny/>\n\nHe continued to appear with his revue in Chicago [[nightclub]]s through most of the 1950s. His last credited performance was in 1958.  After that, he gave up the music business except for occasionally playing in his local neighborhood.  He died in Chicago in 1988, aged about 70.<ref name=penny/>\n\nHis early recordings were anthologised on CD by the French label, [[Chronological Classics]], in 2004.<ref name=penny/><ref name=marion/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adams, Jo Jo}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American musicians]]\n[[Category:American male dancers]]\n[[Category:Jive singers]]\n[[Category:Jump blues musicians]]\n[[Category:Singers from Alabama]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dancers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Joel Adams''' (c.1918 &ndash; February 27, 1988),<ref name=\"bare\">{{cite book| first1= Bob| last1= Eagle| first2= Eric S.| last2= LeBlanc| year= 2013| title= Blues - A Regional Experience| publisher= Praeger Publishers| location= Santa Barbara| pages=534 | isbn= 978-0313344237}}</ref> sometimes credited as '''Doctor Jo-Jo Adams''', was an [[United States|American]] [[jump blues]] singer, comedian, dancer, and [[MC]], who recorded in the 1940s and 1950s.\n\nHe was born in a rural area of [[Alabama]], and sang with the Big Four Gospel Jubilee Singers before moving to [[Chicago]] in the early 1940s.  He then began performing in clubs on the [[South Side of Chicago]], adopting a style derivative of [[Cab Calloway]], wearing a [[tuxedo]] with extended [[Tailcoat|tails]] that would swing around while he danced.  He said: \"I introduced color to the stage. My tailor-made tails that were 55 inches long - when I spun around you could shoot dice on them!\"<ref name=penny>[http://www.rockabilly.nl/references/messages/jo_jo_adams.htm  Dave Penny, \"Jo Jo Adams\", ''Black Cat Rockabilly'']. Retrieved 2 April 2014</ref>\n\nIn 1946 he made his first recording, \"Jo Jo Blues\", with bandleader Freddie Williams for the Melody Lane [[record label]], soon to be renamed [[Hy-Tone]].  He also recorded for Hy-Tone with guitarist [[Floyd Smith (musician)|Floyd Smith]], including the [[marijuana]]-related song \"When I'm In My Tea\"; and recorded for the [[Aladdin Records|Aladdin]] label in [[Los Angeles]] with [[Maxwell Davis]]' band. After returning to Chicago, he recorded under [[Tom Archia]]'s supervision for the [[Aristocrat Records|Aristocrat]] label run by [[Leonard Chess]].<ref name=marion>[http://home.earthlink.net/~v1tiger/drjojo.html  J. C. Marion, \"Doctor Jo Jo Adams\", ''Jamm Upp'' #46, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303200105/http://home.earthlink.net/~v1tiger/drjojo.html |date=2016-03-03 }}. Retrieved 2 April 2014</ref>  His recordings there included \"Cabbage Head\", a version of the folk song \"Our Gudeman\", also known as \"[[Seven Drunken Nights]]\".<ref name=penny/>\n\nAdams appeared in the 1949 all-[[African American]] [[revue]] film ''[[Burlesque in Harlem]]'', performing a risqu\u00e9 version of \"[[The Hucklebuck]]\".  The following year, he began appearing regularly with [[Memphis Slim]] and [[Terry Timmons]] in clubs in Chicago, and at the end of the year performed at a New Year's Eve show with [[Lester Young]] and others.  He also performed in his own revue, the \"Jo Jo Show\", which at various times featured singers [[Joe Williams (jazz singer)|Joe Williams]], [[Willie Mabon]], Bill Pinkard, and the Melvin Moore Combo.<ref name=marion/> He made his last recordings in 1952 and 1953, for the [[Chance Records|Chance]] and [[Parrot Records (blues label)|Parrot]] labels; some of the latter recordings were arranged by [[Sun Ra]].<ref name=penny/>\n\nHe continued to appear with his revue in Chicago [[nightclub]]s through most of the 1950s. His last credited performance was in 1958.  After that, he gave up the music business except for occasionally playing in his local neighborhood.  He died in Chicago in 1988, aged about 70.<ref name=penny/>\n\nHis early recordings were anthologised on CD by the French label, [[Chronological Classics]], in 2004.<ref name=penny/><ref name=marion/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adams, Jo Jo}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American musicians]]\n[[Category:American male dancers]]\n[[Category:Jive singers]]\n[[Category:Jump blues musicians]]\n[[Category:Singers from Alabama]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dancers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jo_Jo_Adams"}
{"title_page": "Don Harron", "text_new": "{{Infobox comedian\n| name              = Don Harron\n| image             = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = Donald Hugh Harron\n| birth_date        = {{birth date|1924|9|19}}\n| birth_place       = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|2015|1|17|1924|9|19}}\n| death_place       = Toronto, Ontario, Canada\n| medium            = [[Television]]\n| nationality       = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| active            = 1935\u20132013\n| genre             = [[Satire]], [[character comedy]]\n| subject           = Current events, rural humour\n| spouse            = {{ubl|{{marriage|Gloria Fisher|1949|1960|reason=divorced}}|{{marriage|[[Virginia Leith]]|1960|1968|reason=divorced}}|{{marriage|[[Catherine McKinnon (actress)|Catherine McKinnon]]|1969|2003|reason=divorced}}|{{marriage|Claudette Gareau|2012}}}}\n| children          = Martha, [[Mary Harron|Mary]], Kelley\n| notable_work      = {{ubl|Charlie Farquharson|''[[Anne of Green Gables \u2013 The Musical]]''|''[[Morningside (radio program)|Morningside]]''}}\n}}\n\n'''Donald Hugh Harron''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|OC|OOnt}} (September 19, 1924 \u2013 January 17, 2015) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] comedian, actor, director, journalist, author, playwright, and composer.  Harron is best remembered by American audiences as a member of the cast of the long-running country music series ''[[Hee Haw]]'', on which he played his signature character of Charlie Farquharson.\n\n==Early life==\nHarron's parents owned and operated Harron's Cleaners and Dyers in Toronto.<ref name=50Plus2004/> Beginning at the age of ten, he earned extra money for the family during the [[Great Depression]], doing  \"chalk talks\" telling humorous stories while drawing caricatures in coloured chalk at company or club banquets, making $10 or $15 a talk.<ref name=50Plus2004/> As a result of his performances, he was invited to audition for, and won, a part in the [[Canadian Radio Broadcasting Commission]] radio series ''Lonesome Trail'' in 1935.<ref name=50Plus2004/><ref>{{cite news|title=Don Harron and his alter ego, Charlie Farquharson (Did You Know?)|url=http://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/arts-entertainment/humour/general-7/don-harron-and-his-alter-ego-charlie-farquharson.html|accessdate=January 18, 2015|work=CBC Digital Archives|date=October 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs a teenager, Harron spent time working as a [[farm hand]] in rural Ontario; experience he later credited for the development of his Charlie Farquharson character.<ref name=cbcobit/> He graduated from [[Vaughan Road Collegiate Institute]] in 1942 and briefly attended the [[University of Toronto]] before enlisting in the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] in 1943. After the [[Second World War]], he completed his studies of sociology and philosophy receiving  a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree. While at school he performed in amateur and professional productions, won the Victoria College drama award, and composed the music and lyrics for a student musical. He won the gold medal in philosophy and the regent's silver medal and was offered a position teaching literature at the university which he turned down in order to focus on performing.<ref name=50Plus2004/>\n\n==Career==\nAfter university, Harron appeared in a number of plays and revues in Toronto, including the annual ''Spring Thaw'' revue, giving him national exposure when the 1952 edition was broadcast on the newly launched [[CBC Television]] network.<ref name=cbcobit/> He spent two years in [[London, England]], travelling there variously performing in a  [[West End of London|West End]] production of ''[[A Streetcar Named Desire (play)|A Streetcar Named Desire]]'' and also working for the [[BBC]] as a comedy writer, acting in a radio series, playing the part of a clown in the film ''[[The Red Shoes (1948 film)|The Red Shoes]]'' (1948) and writing scripts for [[Gracie Fields]].<ref name=50Plus2004/>\n\nReturning to North America in the 1950s, Harron was featured in the inaugural season of the [[Stratford Shakespeare Festival]] in [[Ontario]] as the male lead in ''[[All's Well That Ends Well]]'' and a minor part in {{italics correction|''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]''}}<ref name=cbcobit/> and on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]<ref name=50Plus2004/> and was one of the writers on the first English-language dramatic series broadcast in Canada, ''[[Sunshine Sketches (TV series)|Sunshine Sketches]]'', which aired from 1952 to 1953 on [[CBC Television]].<ref>[http://www.broadcasting-history.ca/index3.html?url=http%3A//www.broadcasting-history.ca/programming/television/programming_popup.php%3Fid%3D750 John Corcelli, ''Sunshine Sketches'', Canadian Communications Foundation, February 2005] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060811/http://www.broadcasting-history.ca/index3.html?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.broadcasting-history.ca%2Fprogramming%2Ftelevision%2Fprogramming_popup.php%3Fid%3D750 |date=2016-03-04 }}</ref> Harron also co-wrote the script for the 1956 television musical ''[[Anne of Green Gables (1956 film)|Anne of Green Gables]]''. Harron later adapted the production for the stage in 1965 as ''[[Anne of Green Gables: The Musical]]'', which continues to be performed annually during the [[Charlottetown Festival]].<ref name=cbcobit/> According to Harron in a 2008 interview with the ''[[Calgary Herald]]'', the stage show has provided work for more than 10,000 actors since its inception.\n\nHarron played Art Harris in the two-part ''[[The Outer Limits (1963 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]'' episode titled \"[[The Inheritors (The Outer Limits)|The Inheritors]]\" (1964), in the ''[[Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea (TV series)|Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea]]'' (\"Doomsday\", 1965) as the naval missile officer aboard the [[SSRN Seaview|SSRN ''Seaview'']] who could not bring himself to perform his duties to launch nuclear missiles and   ''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'' (\"The Four-Steps Affair\", also 1965) as an Australian U.N.C.L.E. agent named Kitt Kittridge. In Twelve O' Clock High (\"The Ticket\", 1965) as LT. Crain.<ref>Title credits as Donald Harron</ref> He guest-starred in the premiere episode of the television series ''[[Blue Light (TV series)|Blue Light]]'' (1966), which was later edited together with the three following episodes to create the theatrical film ''[[I Deal in Danger]]''. Herron starred in the original 1965 [[television pilot]] of [[The Man Who Never Was (TV series)|The Man Who Never Was]] as Mark Wainwright but a change in sponsor led to the new sponsor requesting Robert Lansing in the role<ref>pp.260-262 Harron, Don ''My Double Life: Sexty Yeers of Farquharson Around with Don Harn'' Dundurn, 17 Nov. 2012</ref>.  \n\nHe made one appearance on the [[CBC Television]] show ''[[Adventures in Rainbow Country]]'' in the episode \"The Frank Williams File\" (1969). He has also been a host and interviewer on Canadian television and radio, hosting [[CBC Radio One|CBC Radio]]'s ''[[Morningside (radio program)|Morningside]]'' from 1977 to 1982, for which he received an [[ACTRA Award]] for best radio host,<ref name=cbcobit/> and subsequently hosting an afternoon talk show, ''The Don Harron Show'' on [[CTV television network|CTV]] from 1983 to 1985. He had a featured role in [[Arthur Hiller]]'s film ''[[The Hospital]]'' (1971), written by [[Paddy Chayefsky]]. Harron also appeared on ''[[The Red Green Show]]'' and replaced Gene Wood as host of the game show ''[[Anything You Can Do (game show)|Anything You Can Do]]'' from 1972 to 1974.\n\n=== Charlie Farquharson ===\nHarron is known for the character Charlie Farquharson {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|f|\u0251r|k|\u0259|s|\u0259n}}, a personality he first portrayed in 1952 on the CBC series ''[[The Big Revue]]''. For the following half-century-plus, Harron performed the character regularly on stage and on Canadian radio and television.  As well, the character received international attention as part of the cast of the [[United States|U.S.]] [[country music]] television show, ''[[Hee Haw]]'' during its 23-year run;<ref name=cbcobit/> on that series, which ran from 1969 to 1992, Harron portrayed a rural anchorman for station KORN, and concluded the final story of each newscast with a [[Taunting|cutthroat]] gesture. Harron reprised the character in three episodes of ''[[The Red Green Show]]'' in 2003 and 2004.\n\nDressed in an overly well-worn sweater along with a frayed cap, and sporting a grizzled 'two-day beard,' Farquharson is a decidedly rural Ontario farmer from the real-life town of [[Parry Sound, Ontario|Parry Sound]].  He and his wife, Valeda, have a son, Orville.  Both were usually unseen and unheard, but on occasion (mostly on stage) Harron's wife [[Catherine McKinnon]] would play the role of Valeda. Uneducated, but not without a boisterous 'school of hard knocks' sensibility, Charlie would loudly deliver his opinion about matters local and worldwide, using many [[malapropism]]s in the process which often resulted in both [[double entendre|double meanings]] and increased [[satire]] about the events. He was also known for his loud hearty laugh, \"''Hee! Hee! Hee!''\". In addition to his television appearances as Charlie, through the 1970s and 80s Harron provided humorous syndicated commentaries to various Canadian radio stations in the Farquharson persona. As well, he published several books in the persona of the character, reproducing the malapropisms in print and including strange photos and woodcuts as illustrations.\n\nExamples of Farquharson's comments:\n*\"Nowadaze Parry Sound looks like most uther towns on this continence, thanks to them branched plants of frenchfrises that has sprung up everywhere&nbsp;\u2013 [[McDonald's|Mickdonald's]], [[Burger King|Burglar King]], [[Muammar al-Gaddafi|Kernel Kadaffy]] [[Kentucky Fried Chicken|Frayed Chicken]]. Noware will ya see a sine \"Home Cookin'\", cuz all our lo-cal burghers is out eaten them malty-nashnul burgurs. This makes everplace into a no place, and it's eezy to fergit ware you is if yer jist passin through at snacktime.\" [from ''Cum Buy The Farm'', 1987, p. 11]\n*\"Every guvmint estimit incloods an extry estimit of how much more it's gonna cost than yer ferst estimit. That's how come they always leeve this big deficit on the floor of yer [[House of Commons of Canada|House]]. And a deficit is what you've got wen you haven't got as much as if you jist had nothin'. If we tried any of this, we'd end up in jail. But the guvmint gits rid of its detts by Nashnullizing them. That's like the alkyholick who solved his problem by poring the booze in all of his bottles into one big container. Himself.\" [from ''Charlie Farquharson's K-O-R-N Filled Allmynack'', 1976, pg. 79]\n\nOn May 15, 2011, Don performed the Charlie Farquharson character during the 85th anniversary of his Toronto high school, [[Vaughan Road Collegiate Institute]].\n\n==Honours==\nIn 2000, Harron's contribution to the Canadian entertainment industry was recognized with his being named a member of the [[Order of Ontario]].  He was invested as member of the [[Order of Canada]] in 1980 and in 2007, he was given the [[Gemini Award]] for Lifetime Achievement in Radio and Television.<ref name=cbcobit/> Harron was also appointed a [[United Nations Children's Fund|UNICEF]] [[List of UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors|Goodwill Ambassador]].  In his later years, he was a high-profile advocate for the interests of older people. He also continued to write books, most recently (2008) publishing a retrospective work on the history of the ''Anne of Green Gables'' musical to tie in with the 100th anniversary of the original novel.\n\nHarron was inducted into the [[Canadian Country Music Hall of Fame]] in 2010.<ref name=\"ccma\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ccma.org/halloffame/hofprofile.cfm?AwardID=805|title=Don Harron biography|work=[[Canadian Country Music Association]]|accessdate=1 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929074540/http://www.ccma.org/halloffame/hofprofile.cfm?AwardID=805|archivedate=29 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nHarron's first marriage was to Gloria Fisher, his second from 1960-1968 was to actress [[Virginia Leith]]. He married his third wife, Canadian singer [[Catherine McKinnon (actress)|Catherine McKinnon]] in 1969.<ref name=50Plus2004>{{cite news |url=http://www.everythingzoomer.com/printview/?postid=32597 |title=The life, loves and regrets of Don Harron |first=Alex |last=Budman |website=Everythingzoomer.com |date=January 1, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924004333/http://www.everythingzoomer.com/printview/?postid=32597 |archive-date=September 24, 2015}}</ref> Harron and McKinnon divorced in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.toronto.com/news-story/1936875-comedian-don-harron-opens-up-in-latest-book/ |title=Comedian Don Harron, opens up in latest book |first=Hilary |last=Caton |website=Toronto.com |date=February 2, 2013}}</ref> He moved in with and later married his fourth wife, Claudette Gareau, who had played the separatist weather girl in ''Shh! It\u2019s the News'' (1973) appearing with Harron.<ref name=50Plus2004/>\n\nHarron's daughter [[Mary Harron]]<ref>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=M1ARTM0012165 Canadian Encyclopedia] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607145511/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=M1ARTM0012165 |date=June 7, 2011 }} bio of Mary Harron</ref> from his marriage to Fisher, is an independent film director whose credits include ''[[I Shot Andy Warhol]]'' and ''[[American Psycho]]''.<ref name=cbcobit/> She directed \"Alias Grace\" which won the 2018 Canadian Screen Award for Best Limited Series.\n\nHarron died at 90 surrounded by his family in his Toronto home after deciding not to seek treatment for his cancer. His daughter, Martha, told [[Canadian Press]] \"He was still sharp. He was still capable of being funny even though his voice was barely above a whisper... It's horribly sad, but it's beautiful too.\"<ref name=cbcobit>{{cite news|title=Don Harron, Canadian entertainment icon, dead at 90|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/don-harron-canadian-entertainment-icon-dead-at-90-1.2916802|accessdate=January 17, 2015|work=CBC News|date=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Selected bibliography ==\nHarron authored 17 books \u2013 most of them in character as Charlie Farquharson with titles spelled in the character's [[idiolect]], as well as his 2012 memoir:<ref name=cbcobit/>\n* ''Charlie Farquharson's Histry <!-- sic - \"Histry\" is actual spelling -->of Canada'' (McGraw-Hill Ryerson, 1972) {{ISBN|0-07-092530-5}}\n* ''Charlie Farquharson's Jogfree of Canda'' <!-- sic - \"Canda\" is actual spelling -->(Gage, 1974)\n* ''Charlie Farquharson's K-O-R-N Filled Allmynack'' (Gage, 1976)\n* ''Olde Charlie Farquharson's Testament: From Jennysez to Jobe and After Words'' (MacMillan of Canada, 1978) {{ISBN|0-7715-9900-5}}\n* ''Yer Last Decadent: 1972-1982'' (MacMillan of Canada, 1982)\n* ''Cum Buy The Farm'' (MacMillan of Canada 1987)\n* ''Charlie Farquharson's Unyverse'' (MacMillan of Canada, 1990)\n* ''Charlie Farquharson's History of Canada: ReeVised and More Expansive'' (MacMillan of Canada, 1992)\n* ''Charlie's A Broad: Travails In Fern Parts'' (MacMillan of Canada, 1994)\n* ''My Double Life: Sexty Yeers of Farquharson Around With Don Harn'' (Dundurn 2012)\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1952|| ''[[The Sound Barrier]]'' || ATA Officer || Uncredited\n|-\n|1959|| ''[[The Best of Everything (film)|The Best of Everything]]'' || Sidney Carter ||\n|-\n|1965|| ''[[The Spy with My Face]]'' || Kittridge ||\n|-\n|1966|| ''[[I Deal in Danger]]'' || Spauling ||\n|-\n|1967|| ''Mosby's Marauders'' || Gen. Stoughton ||\n|-\n|1971|| ''[[The Hospital]]'' || Milton Mead ||\n|-\n|1975|| ''The Human Collision'' || ||\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|365999}}\n* {{IBDB name | 5080 }}\n* {{iobdb name|24836}}\n* {{YouTube|id=L-v9_zvWS24|title=\"Don Harron interview at Theatre Museum Canada\"}}\n* {{findagrave|141537148}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harron, Don}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Canadian stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:Canadian humorists]]\n[[Category:Canadian musical theatre librettists]]\n[[Category:Canadian television writers]]\n[[Category:CBC Radio hosts]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Toronto]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male actors]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Canadian male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian musicians]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian comedians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox comedian\n| name              = Don Harron\n| image             = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = Donald Hugh Harron\n| birth_date        = {{birth date|1924|9|19}}\n| birth_place       = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|2015|1|17|1924|9|19}}\n| death_place       = Toronto, Ontario, Canada\n| medium            = [[Television]]\n| nationality       = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| active            = 1935\u20132013\n| genre             = [[Satire]], [[character comedy]]\n| subject           = Current events, rural humour\n| spouse            = {{ubl|{{marriage|Gloria Fisher|1949|1960|reason=divorced}}|{{marriage|[[Virginia Leith]]|1960|1968|reason=divorced}}|{{marriage|[[Catherine McKinnon (actress)|Catherine McKinnon]]|1969|2003|reason=divorced}}|{{marriage|Claudette Gareau|2012}}}}\n| children          = Martha, [[Mary Harron|Mary]], Kelley\n| notable_work      = {{ubl|Charlie Farquharson|''[[Anne of Green Gables \u2013 The Musical]]''|''[[Morningside (radio program)|Morningside]]''}}\n}}\n\n'''Donald Hugh Harron''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|OC|OOnt}} (September 19, 1924 \u2013 January 17, 2015) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] comedian, actor, director, journalist, author, playwright, and composer.  Harron is best remembered by American audiences as a member of the cast of the long-running country music series ''[[Hee Haw]]'', on which he played his signature character of Charlie Farquharson.\n\n==Early life==\nHarron's parents owned and operated Harron's Cleaners and Dyers in Toronto.<ref name=50Plus2004/> Beginning at the age of ten, he earned extra money for the family during the [[Great Depression]], doing  \"chalk talks\" telling humorous stories while drawing caricatures in coloured chalk at company or club banquets, making $10 or $15 a talk.<ref name=50Plus2004/> As a result of his performances, he was invited to audition for, and won, a part in the [[Canadian Radio Broadcasting Commission]] radio series ''Lonesome Trail'' in 1935.<ref name=50Plus2004/><ref>{{cite news|title=Don Harron and his alter ego, Charlie Farquharson (Did You Know?)|url=http://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/arts-entertainment/humour/general-7/don-harron-and-his-alter-ego-charlie-farquharson.html|accessdate=January 18, 2015|work=CBC Digital Archives|date=October 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs a teenager, Harron spent time working as a [[farm hand]] in rural Ontario; experience he later credited for the development of his Charlie Farquharson character.<ref name=cbcobit/> He graduated from [[Vaughan Road Collegiate Institute]] in 1942 and briefly attended the [[University of Toronto]] before enlisting in the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] in 1943. After the [[Second World War]], he completed his studies of sociology and philosophy receiving  a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree. While at school he performed in amateur and professional productions, won the Victoria College drama award, and composed the music and lyrics for a student musical. He won the gold medal in philosophy and the regent's silver medal and was offered a position teaching literature at the university which he turned down in order to focus on performing.<ref name=50Plus2004/>\n\n==Career==\nAfter university, Harron appeared in a number of plays and revues in Toronto, including the annual ''Spring Thaw'' revue, giving him national exposure when the 1952 edition was broadcast on the newly launched [[CBC Television]] network.<ref name=cbcobit/> He spent two years in [[London, England]], travelling there variously performing in a  [[West End of London|West End]] production of ''[[A Streetcar Named Desire (play)|A Streetcar Named Desire]]'' and also working for the [[BBC]] as a comedy writer, acting in a radio series, playing the part of a clown in the film ''[[The Red Shoes (1948 film)|The Red Shoes]]'' (1948) and writing scripts for [[Gracie Fields]].<ref name=50Plus2004/>\n\nReturning to North America in the 1950s, Harron was featured in the inaugural season of the [[Stratford Shakespeare Festival]] in [[Ontario]] as the male lead in ''[[All's Well That Ends Well]]'' and a minor part in {{italics correction|''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]''}}<ref name=cbcobit/> and on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]<ref name=50Plus2004/> and was one of the writers on the first English-language dramatic series broadcast in Canada, ''[[Sunshine Sketches (TV series)|Sunshine Sketches]]'', which aired from 1952 to 1953 on [[CBC Television]].<ref>[http://www.broadcasting-history.ca/index3.html?url=http%3A//www.broadcasting-history.ca/programming/television/programming_popup.php%3Fid%3D750 John Corcelli, ''Sunshine Sketches'', Canadian Communications Foundation, February 2005] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060811/http://www.broadcasting-history.ca/index3.html?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.broadcasting-history.ca%2Fprogramming%2Ftelevision%2Fprogramming_popup.php%3Fid%3D750 |date=2016-03-04 }}</ref> Harron also co-wrote the script for the 1956 television musical ''[[Anne of Green Gables (1956 film)|Anne of Green Gables]]''. Harron later adapted the production for the stage in 1965 as ''[[Anne of Green Gables: The Musical]]'', which continues to be performed annually during the [[Charlottetown Festival]].<ref name=cbcobit/> According to Harron in a 2008 interview with the ''[[Calgary Herald]]'', the stage show has provided work for more than 10,000 actors since its inception.\n\nHarron played Art Harris in the two-part ''[[The Outer Limits (1963 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]'' episode titled \"[[The Inheritors (The Outer Limits)|The Inheritors]]\" (1964), in the ''[[Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea (TV series)|Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea]]'' (\"Doomsday\", 1965) as the naval missile officer aboard the [[SSRN Seaview|SSRN ''Seaview'']] who could not bring himself to perform his duties to launch nuclear missiles and   ''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'' (\"The Four-Steps Affair\", also 1965) as an Australian U.N.C.L.E. agent named Kitt Kittridge. In Twelve O' Clock High (\"The Ticket\", 1965) as LT. Crain.<ref>Title credits as Donald Harron</ref> He guest-starred in the premiere episode of the television series ''[[Blue Light (TV series)|Blue Light]]'' (1966), which was later edited together with the three following episodes to create the theatrical film ''[[I Deal in Danger]]''. Herron starred in the original 1965 [[television pilot]] of [[The Man Who Never Was (TV series)|The Man Who Never Was]] as Mark Wainwright but a change in sponsor led to the new sponsor requesting Robert Lansing in the role<ref>pp.260-262 Harron, Don ''My Double Life: Sexty Yeers of Farquharson Around with Don Harn'' Dundurn, 17 Nov. 2012</ref>.  \n\nHe made one appearance on the [[CBC Television]] show ''[[Adventures in Rainbow Country]]'' in the episode \"The Frank Williams File\" (1969). He has also been a host and interviewer on Canadian television and radio, hosting [[CBC Radio One|CBC Radio]]'s ''[[Morningside (radio program)|Morningside]]'' from 1977 to 1982, for which he received an [[ACTRA Award]] for best radio host,<ref name=cbcobit/> and subsequently hosting an afternoon talk show, ''The Don Harron Show'' on [[CTV television network|CTV]] from 1983 to 1985. He had a featured role in [[Arthur Hiller]]'s film ''[[The Hospital]]'' (1971), written by [[Paddy Chayevsky]]. Harron also appeared on ''[[The Red Green Show]]'' and replaced Gene Wood as host of the game show ''[[Anything You Can Do (game show)|Anything You Can Do]]'' from 1972 to 1974.\n\n=== Charlie Farquharson ===\nHarron is known for the character Charlie Farquharson {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|f|\u0251r|k|\u0259|s|\u0259n}}, a personality he first portrayed in 1952 on the CBC series ''[[The Big Revue]]''. For the following half-century-plus, Harron performed the character regularly on stage and on Canadian radio and television.  As well, the character received international attention as part of the cast of the [[United States|U.S.]] [[country music]] television show, ''[[Hee Haw]]'' during its 23-year run;<ref name=cbcobit/> on that series, which ran from 1969 to 1992, Harron portrayed a rural anchorman for station KORN, and concluded the final story of each newscast with a [[Taunting|cutthroat]] gesture. Harron reprised the character in three episodes of ''[[The Red Green Show]]'' in 2003 and 2004.\n\nDressed in an overly well-worn sweater along with a frayed cap, and sporting a grizzled 'two-day beard,' Farquharson is a decidedly rural Ontario farmer from the real-life town of [[Parry Sound, Ontario|Parry Sound]].  He and his wife, Valeda, have a son, Orville.  Both were usually unseen and unheard, but on occasion (mostly on stage) Harron's wife [[Catherine McKinnon]] would play the role of Valeda. Uneducated, but not without a boisterous 'school of hard knocks' sensibility, Charlie would loudly deliver his opinion about matters local and worldwide, using many [[malapropism]]s in the process which often resulted in both [[double entendre|double meanings]] and increased [[satire]] about the events. He was also known for his loud hearty laugh, \"''Hee! Hee! Hee!''\". In addition to his television appearances as Charlie, through the 1970s and 80s Harron provided humorous syndicated commentaries to various Canadian radio stations in the Farquharson persona. As well, he published several books in the persona of the character, reproducing the malapropisms in print and including strange photos and woodcuts as illustrations.\n\nExamples of Farquharson's comments:\n*\"Nowadaze Parry Sound looks like most uther towns on this continence, thanks to them branched plants of frenchfrises that has sprung up everywhere&nbsp;\u2013 [[McDonald's|Mickdonald's]], [[Burger King|Burglar King]], [[Muammar al-Gaddafi|Kernel Kadaffy]] [[Kentucky Fried Chicken|Frayed Chicken]]. Noware will ya see a sine \"Home Cookin'\", cuz all our lo-cal burghers is out eaten them malty-nashnul burgurs. This makes everplace into a no place, and it's eezy to fergit ware you is if yer jist passin through at snacktime.\" [from ''Cum Buy The Farm'', 1987, p. 11]\n*\"Every guvmint estimit incloods an extry estimit of how much more it's gonna cost than yer ferst estimit. That's how come they always leeve this big deficit on the floor of yer [[House of Commons of Canada|House]]. And a deficit is what you've got wen you haven't got as much as if you jist had nothin'. If we tried any of this, we'd end up in jail. But the guvmint gits rid of its detts by Nashnullizing them. That's like the alkyholick who solved his problem by poring the booze in all of his bottles into one big container. Himself.\" [from ''Charlie Farquharson's K-O-R-N Filled Allmynack'', 1976, pg. 79]\n\nOn May 15, 2011, Don performed the Charlie Farquharson character during the 85th anniversary of his Toronto high school, [[Vaughan Road Collegiate Institute]].\n\n==Honours==\nIn 2000, Harron's contribution to the Canadian entertainment industry was recognized with his being named a member of the [[Order of Ontario]].  He was invested as member of the [[Order of Canada]] in 1980 and in 2007, he was given the [[Gemini Award]] for Lifetime Achievement in Radio and Television.<ref name=cbcobit/> Harron was also appointed a [[United Nations Children's Fund|UNICEF]] [[List of UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors|Goodwill Ambassador]].  In his later years, he was a high-profile advocate for the interests of older people. He also continued to write books, most recently (2008) publishing a retrospective work on the history of the ''Anne of Green Gables'' musical to tie in with the 100th anniversary of the original novel.\n\nHarron was inducted into the [[Canadian Country Music Hall of Fame]] in 2010.<ref name=\"ccma\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ccma.org/halloffame/hofprofile.cfm?AwardID=805|title=Don Harron biography|work=[[Canadian Country Music Association]]|accessdate=1 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929074540/http://www.ccma.org/halloffame/hofprofile.cfm?AwardID=805|archivedate=29 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nHarron's first marriage was to Gloria Fisher, his second from 1960-1968 was to actress [[Virginia Leith]]. He married his third wife, Canadian singer [[Catherine McKinnon (actress)|Catherine McKinnon]] in 1969.<ref name=50Plus2004>{{cite news |url=http://www.everythingzoomer.com/printview/?postid=32597 |title=The life, loves and regrets of Don Harron |first=Alex |last=Budman |website=Everythingzoomer.com |date=January 1, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924004333/http://www.everythingzoomer.com/printview/?postid=32597 |archive-date=September 24, 2015}}</ref> Harron and McKinnon divorced in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.toronto.com/news-story/1936875-comedian-don-harron-opens-up-in-latest-book/ |title=Comedian Don Harron, opens up in latest book |first=Hilary |last=Caton |website=Toronto.com |date=February 2, 2013}}</ref> He moved in with and later married his fourth wife, Claudette Gareau, who had played the separatist weather girl in ''Shh! It\u2019s the News'' (1973) appearing with Harron.<ref name=50Plus2004/>\n\nHarron's daughter [[Mary Harron]]<ref>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=M1ARTM0012165 Canadian Encyclopedia] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607145511/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=M1ARTM0012165 |date=June 7, 2011 }} bio of Mary Harron</ref> from his marriage to Fisher, is an independent film director whose credits include ''[[I Shot Andy Warhol]]'' and ''[[American Psycho]]''.<ref name=cbcobit/> She directed \"Alias Grace\" which won the 2018 Canadian Screen Award for Best Limited Series.\n\nHarron died at 90 surrounded by his family in his Toronto home after deciding not to seek treatment for his cancer. His daughter, Martha, told [[Canadian Press]] \"He was still sharp. He was still capable of being funny even though his voice was barely above a whisper... It's horribly sad, but it's beautiful too.\"<ref name=cbcobit>{{cite news|title=Don Harron, Canadian entertainment icon, dead at 90|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/don-harron-canadian-entertainment-icon-dead-at-90-1.2916802|accessdate=January 17, 2015|work=CBC News|date=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Selected bibliography ==\nHarron authored 17 books \u2013 most of them in character as Charlie Farquharson with titles spelled in the character's [[idiolect]], as well as his 2012 memoir:<ref name=cbcobit/>\n* ''Charlie Farquharson's Histry <!-- sic - \"Histry\" is actual spelling -->of Canada'' (McGraw-Hill Ryerson, 1972) {{ISBN|0-07-092530-5}}\n* ''Charlie Farquharson's Jogfree of Canda'' <!-- sic - \"Canda\" is actual spelling -->(Gage, 1974)\n* ''Charlie Farquharson's K-O-R-N Filled Allmynack'' (Gage, 1976)\n* ''Olde Charlie Farquharson's Testament: From Jennysez to Jobe and After Words'' (MacMillan of Canada, 1978) {{ISBN|0-7715-9900-5}}\n* ''Yer Last Decadent: 1972-1982'' (MacMillan of Canada, 1982)\n* ''Cum Buy The Farm'' (MacMillan of Canada 1987)\n* ''Charlie Farquharson's Unyverse'' (MacMillan of Canada, 1990)\n* ''Charlie Farquharson's History of Canada: ReeVised and More Expansive'' (MacMillan of Canada, 1992)\n* ''Charlie's A Broad: Travails In Fern Parts'' (MacMillan of Canada, 1994)\n* ''My Double Life: Sexty Yeers of Farquharson Around With Don Harn'' (Dundurn 2012)\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1952|| ''[[The Sound Barrier]]'' || ATA Officer || Uncredited\n|-\n|1959|| ''[[The Best of Everything (film)|The Best of Everything]]'' || Sidney Carter ||\n|-\n|1965|| ''[[The Spy with My Face]]'' || Kittridge ||\n|-\n|1966|| ''[[I Deal in Danger]]'' || Spauling ||\n|-\n|1967|| ''Mosby's Marauders'' || Gen. Stoughton ||\n|-\n|1971|| ''[[The Hospital]]'' || Milton Mead ||\n|-\n|1975|| ''The Human Collision'' || ||\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|365999}}\n* {{IBDB name | 5080 }}\n* {{iobdb name|24836}}\n* {{YouTube|id=L-v9_zvWS24|title=\"Don Harron interview at Theatre Museum Canada\"}}\n* {{findagrave|141537148}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harron, Don}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Canadian stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:Canadian humorists]]\n[[Category:Canadian musical theatre librettists]]\n[[Category:Canadian television writers]]\n[[Category:CBC Radio hosts]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Toronto]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male actors]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Canadian male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian musicians]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian comedians]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_Harron"}
{"title_page": "Sergio Reguil\u00f3n", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Reguil\u00f3n|Rodr\u00edguez}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Sergio Reguil\u00f3n\n| image = Sergio Reguil\u00f3n 2018.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = Reguil\u00f3n playing for [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in 2018\n| fullname = Sergio Reguil\u00f3n Rodr\u00edguez<ref>{{cite web |url=http://actas.rfef.es/actas/RFEF_CmpActa1?cod_primaria=1000144&CodActa=42201 |title=Acta del Partido celebrado el 07 de mayo de 2017, en Amorebieta-Etxano |trans-title=Minutes of the Match held on 7 May 2017, in Amorebieta-Etxano |publisher=Royal Spanish Football Federation |accessdate=15 June 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1996|12|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Madrid]], Spain\n| height = {{height|m=1.80}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/football/squad/sergio-reguilon-rodriguez--|title=Sergio Reguil\u00f3n|accessdate=30 July 2018}}</ref>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Left back]]\n| currentclub = [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]]<br>(on loan from [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]])\n| clubnumber = 23\n| youthyears1 = 2000\u20132003 | youthclubs1 = [[La F\u00e1brica|Fundaci\u00f3n RM Becerril]]\n| youthyears2 = 2003\u20132005 | youthclubs2 = EFM Villalba\n| youthyears3 = 2005\u20132015 | youthclubs3 = [[Real Madrid CF (youth)|Real Madrid]]\n| years1 = 2015\u20132018 | clubs1 = [[Real Madrid Castilla|Real Madrid B]] | caps1 = 44 | goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 2015\u20132016 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s|Logro\u00f1\u00e9s]] (loan) | caps2 = 9 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2016\u20132017 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s|Logro\u00f1\u00e9s]] (loan) | caps3 = 30 | goals3 = 8\n| years4 = 2018\u2013 | clubs4 = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] | caps4 = 14 | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2019\u2013 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] (loan) | caps5 = 18 | goals5 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 2019 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 1| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| club-update = 19:59, 26 January 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''Sergio Reguil\u00f3n Rodr\u00edguez''' (born 16 December 1996) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left back]] for [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]], on loan from [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]].\n[style of play]\nhe is known for his pace and ability to cross the ball\n\n==Club career==\nReguil\u00f3n joined [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]'s youth setup in 2005, aged eight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.es/deportes/real-madrid/abci-sueno-cumplido-sergio-reguilon-201808070129_noticia.html|title=El sue\u00f1o cumplido de Sergio Reguil\u00f3n|trans-title=The fulfilled dream of Sergio Reguil\u00f3n|publisher=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=es|date=7 August 2018|access-date=4 September 2018}}</ref> On 5 August 2015, after finishing his formation, he was loaned to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] side [[UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s]] for [[2015\u201316 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|the season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rioja2.com/n-100011-401-joven_Sergio_Reguilon_llega_UD_Logrones/|title=El joven Sergio Reguil\u00f3n llega al UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s|trans-title=The youngster Sergio Reguil\u00f3n arrives at UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s|publisher=Rioja2|language=es|date=5 August 2015|access-date=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nReguil\u00f3n made his senior debut on 23 August 2015, playing the last seven minutes in a 3\u20130 home win against [[SD Compostela]]. The following 16 January, after being sparingly used, he returned to ''Los Blancos'' and was assigned to [[Real Madrid Castilla|the reserves]] also in the third division.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/futbol/real-madrid/2016/01/16/569a1b28ca4741364e8b4606.html|title=El Castilla mueve el mercado|trans-title=Castilla move the market|publisher=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=16 January 2016|access-date=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 August 2016, Reguil\u00f3n returned to Logro\u00f1\u00e9s also in a one-year loan deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://udlogrones.com/sergio-reguilon-cedido-por-el-madrid-castilla-hasta-final-de-temporada/|title=Sergio Reguil\u00f3n, cedido por el Madrid Castilla hasta final de temporada|trans-title=Sergio Reguil\u00f3n, loaned from Real Madrid Castilla until the end of the season|publisher=UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s|language=es|date=23 August 2016|access-date=4 September 2018}}</ref> Now an undisputed starter, he scored eight goals during [[2016\u201317 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|the campaign]]; highlights included four past [[Bilbao Athletic]] on 2 October 2016 (5\u20133 home win).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rioja2.com/n-106752-4-reguilon-reguilon-reguilon-reguilon/|title=Reguil\u00f3n, Reguil\u00f3n, Reguil\u00f3n, Reguil\u00f3n|publisher=Rioja2|language=es|date=2 October 2016|access-date=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nUpon returning to Castilla, Reguil\u00f3n was a first-choice in [[Santiago Solari]]'s side, and renewed his contract on 11 May 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/futbol/real-madrid/2018/05/11/5af5ace346163f5c4e8b45b5.html|title=Reguil\u00f3n, renovaci\u00f3n 'de primer equipo'|trans-title=Reguil\u00f3n, 'first team' renewal|publisher=Marca|language=es|date=11 May 2018|access-date=4 September 2018}}</ref> On 25 August of that year, he was promoted to the main squad by manager [[Julen Lopetegui]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/real-madrid/20180825/451445104435/reguilon-madrid-lopetegui-marcelo-theo.html|title=Reguil\u00f3n se queda en el primer equipo|trans-title=Reguil\u00f3n stays in the first team|publisher=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|language=es|date=25 August 2018|access-date=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nReguil\u00f3n made his professional debut on 2 October 2018, starting in a 0\u20131 [[UEFA Champions League]] away loss against [[PFC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Juventus win again as CSKA beat Madrid, Ajax hold Bayern|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2573015.html|accessdate=2 October 2018|publisher=UEFA|date=2 October 2018}}</ref> He also made his league debut on 3 November 2018, starting in a 2\u20130 [[La Liga]] home win against [[Real Valladolid]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Vinicius changes Real's luck|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2018/11/03/5bdde14422601df6698b4602.html|accessdate=3 November 2018|publisher=marca.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 July 2019, he was loaned to [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] for the 2019\u201320 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sergio Reguil\u00f3n joins on loan from Real Madrid|url=https://www.sevillafc.es/en/actual/news/sergio-reguilon-joins-loan-real-madrid|accessdate=5 July 2019|publisher=sevillafc.es}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Official Announcement: Reguil\u00f3n|url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2019/07/official-announcement-reguilon|accessdate=5 July 2019|publisher=realmadrid.com}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nHe was selected for the [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain under-21 team]] for the first time by [[Luis de la Fuente Castillo]] for the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] qualifiers against [[Romania national under-21 football team|Romania]] and [[Austria national under-21 football team|Austria]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sefutbol.com/oficial-estos-son-internacionales-que-disputaran-amistosos-rumania-y-austria|title=De La fuente's u-21 squad for 2019 euro qualification|date=15 March 2019|accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref> He received his first call up for the [[Spain national team|full side]] by [[Robert Moreno]] on 4 October 2019, for games against [[Norway national football team|Norway]] and [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2019/10/04/5d971507e2704e76198b4571.html|title=Reguilon, Pau Torres and Gerard Moreno named in Spain squad for first time|date=4 October 2019|website=Marca|language=en|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn in [[Madrid]], his parents are from [[Zamora (Spain)|Zamora]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.laopiniondezamora.es/deportes/2019/03/19/bonito-detalle-zamorano-reguilon-padre/1151556.html |title=El bonito detalle del zamorano Reguil\u00f3n con su padre |author=E. S. D. |date=19 March 2019 |access-date=18 May 2019 |newspaper=La Opini\u00f3n de Zamora |language=es |publisher=Prensa Ib\u00e9ria}}</ref> He is dating the [[YouTuber]] [[Marta D\u00edaz]] .<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.larazon.es/lifestyle/celebrities/marta-diaz-asi-es-el-estilo-de-la-youtuber-novia-de-reguilon-PE23278755 |title=Marta D\u00edaz, as\u00ed es el estilo de la Youtuber novia de Reguil\u00f3n |date=10 May 2019 |access-date=18 May 2019 |newspaper=[[La Raz\u00f3n (Spain)|La Raz\u00f3n]] |language=es}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|25 January 2020}}<ref>{{Soccerway|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" valign=\"center\"|[[Real Madrid Castilla]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2015\u201316]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n|18||0||colspan=6|\u2014||18||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2017\u201318]]\n|30||2||colspan=6|\u2014||30||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!48!!2!!colspan=6|\u2014!!48!!2\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" valign=\"center\"|[[UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s|Logro\u00f1\u00e9s]] (loan)\n|[[2015\u201316 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2015\u201316]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B\n|9||0||3||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||12||0\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2016\u201317]]\n|30||8||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||31||8\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\